Definition 4.2. We define an implicit Runge-Kutta method with $q$-step iterative solution as follows: Choose $s,A,b,h$ as in Definition 2.6. Choose a positive integer $q$ and fix a point $x\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$. Define a map $\underline{X}:(\mathbb{R}^{n})^{s}\to(\mathbb{R}^{n})^{s}$ by $\underline{X}(\xi_{1},\ldots,\xi_{s})=\left(X\left(x+h\sum_{j=1}^{s}a_{1,j}\xi% _{j}\right),\ldots,X\left(x+h\sum_{j=1}^{s}a_{s,j}\xi_{j}\right)\right)$ for all $\boldsymbol{\xi}=(\xi_{1},\ldots,\xi_{s})\in(\mathbb{R}^{n})^{s}$.Choose $\boldsymbol{\xi}^{(0)}=(X(x),\ldots,X(x))$. Define $\boldsymbol{\xi}^{(k+1)}\in(\mathbb{R}^{n})^{s}$ recursively by $\boldsymbol{\xi}^{(k+1)}:=\underline{X}(\boldsymbol{\xi}^{(k)})$ for $k=0,\ldots,q-1$. Now define $D_{X}^{(A,b,h,q)}(x):=x+h\sum_{i=1}^{s}b_{i}\xi_{i}^{(q)}.$
Definition 2.1.3. For a dg category $\mathcal{A}$, its ordinary category $Z^{0}(\mathcal{A})$ is defined as follows: the same objects with $\mathcal{A}$, and morphisms are given by closed morphisms of degree zero. Similarly, the homotopy category $H^{0}(\mathcal{A})$ has the same objects whose morphism spaces are given by the zeroth cohomologies of the Hom-complexes in $\mathcal{A}$.
Definition 2.1.6. A dg functor $F\colon\mathcal{A}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}$ is quasi-fully faithful, if each $F_{x,y}$ is a quasi-isomorphism. If in addition $H^{0}(F)\colon H^{0}(\mathcal{A})\rightarrow H^{0}(\mathcal{B})$ is dense, $F$ is called a quasi-equivalence.
Definition 2.1.1. A dg category $\mathcal{A}$ is a category subject to $\bullet$ ${\rm obj}(\mathcal{A})$: usually denoted by $x,y,z\cdots$ $\bullet$ each Hom set $\mathcal{A}(x,y)$ is a complex, denoted by $\mathcal{A}(x,y)=(\bigoplus_{p\in\mathbb{Z}}\mathcal{A}(x,y)^{p},d_{\mathcal{A% }}).$ The element $f\in\mathcal{A}(x,y)^{p}$ is homogeneous of degree $p$ with the notation $|f|=p$, such that the composition $\mathcal{A}(y,z)\otimes\mathcal{A}(x,y)\longrightarrow\mathcal{A}(x,z)$ is a chain map. In more details, for any homogeneous morphisms $f\colon x\rightarrow y$ and $g\colon y\rightarrow z$, we have $|g\circ f|=|g|+|f|\mbox{ and }d_{\mathcal{A}}(g\circ f)=d_{\mathcal{A}}(g)% \circ f+(-1)^{|g|}g\circ d_{\mathcal{A}}(f).$
Definition 2.1.5. For two dg categories $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$, a dg functor $F\colon\mathcal{A}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}$ is a $k$-linear functor such that $F_{x,y}\colon\mathcal{A}(x,y)\longrightarrow\mathcal{B}(Fx,Fy)$ is a chain map. In other words, $|F(f)|=|f|$ and $F(d_{\mathcal{A}}(f))=d_{\mathcal{B}}(Ff)$.
Definition 3.1.1. A left dg $\mathcal{A}$-module is a dg functor $M\colon\mathcal{A}\rightarrow C_{\rm dg}(k)$. The dg category of left dg $\mathcal{A}$-modules is given by $\mathcal{A}\mbox{-}{\rm DGMod}=\mathcal{H}{om}(\mathcal{A},C_{\rm dg}(k)).$ The Hom-complex between two dg modules $M$ and $M^{\prime}$ is denoted by ${\rm Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(M,M^{\prime})$. By definition, a right dg $\mathcal{A}$-module is a left dg $\mathcal{A}^{\rm op}$-module. Then we have the dg category ${\rm DGMod}\mbox{-}\mathcal{A}$ of right dg $\mathcal{A}$-modules.
Definition 5. Let $(F,\psi)$ be as above. The double colimit of $F$ is an object in $\mathbb{E}_{0}$, denoted $\text{dcolim}F$, equipped with a structure map $\eta:F\Rightarrow\text{dcolim}F$ such that given any other map $\eta^{\prime}:F\Rightarrow x$ for some $x\in\mathbb{E}_{0}$ there is a unique morphism $f:\text{dcolim}F\rightarrow x$ in $E_{0}$ with $f\circ\eta=\eta^{\prime}$. $F$$\text{dcolim}F$$x$$\eta$$\eta^{\prime}$$\exists!f$
Definition 3. An $n$-collage is an $(n+2)$-tuples of categories $(\mathcal{C}_{0},...,\mathcal{C}_{n},\mathcal{C})$ such that $\mathcal{C}$ is a category satisfying: i) $\text{ob}(\mathcal{C})=\coprod_{i=1}^{n}\text{ob}(\mathcal{C}_{i})$ ii) $\mathcal{C}(a,b)=\mathcal{C}_{i}(a,b)$ if $a,b\in\mathcal{C}_{i}$ iii) $\mathcal{C}(a,b)=\emptyset$ if $a\in\mathcal{C}_{i}$, $b\in\mathcal{C}_{j}$ and $i>j$
Definition 2. Let $(F,\alpha)$, $(G,\beta)$ be two horizontal diagrams in a double category $\mathbb{D}$ indexed by a category $\mathcal{J}$. A vertical transformation $\tau:F\Rightarrow G$ consists of: – A vertical morphism $\tau_{i}:F(i)\rightarrow G(i)$ or each $i\in\mathcal{J}$ – A 2-cell $F(i)$$F(j)$$G(i)$$G(j)$$\tau_{i}$$Ff$$\tau_{j}$$Gf$$\tau_{f}$ for each morphism $f:i\rightarrow j$ in $\mathcal{J}$ such that everything commutes, meaning for all composable pairs $i\xrightarrow{f}j\xrightarrow{g}k$ we have $F(i)$$F(j)$$F(k)$$G(i)$$G(j)$$G(k)$$F(i)$$F(k)$$G(i)$$G(k)$$\alpha_{f,g}^{-1}$$\tau_{f}$$\tau_{g}$$\beta_{f,g}$$=$$F(i)$$G(i)$$F(k)$$G(k)$$\tau_{gf}$$F(gf)$$1$$Ff$$Fg$$1$$\tau_{i}$$\tau_{j}$$\tau_{k}$$Gf$$Gg$$1$$1$$G(gf)$ or equationally $\beta_{f,g}(\tau_{g}*\tau_{f})\alpha_{f,g}^{-1}=\tau_{gf}$
Definition 1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ be categories. A collage between $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ is a category $U$ such that: i) the objects of $U$ are precisely those of $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ $\text{ob}(U)=\text{ob}(\mathcal{C})\coprod\text{ob}(\mathcal{D})$ ii) if $c,c^{\prime}\in\mathcal{C}$ then $U(c,c^{\prime})=\mathcal{C}(c,c^{\prime})$ and if $d,d^{\prime}\in\mathcal{D}$ then $U(d,d^{\prime})=\mathcal{D}(d,d^{\prime})$ iii) if $c\in\mathcal{C}$ and $d\in\mathcal{D}$ then $U(d,c)=\emptyset$
Definition 4. Let $\mathbb{E}$ be a simplicial category. $\mathbb{E}$ is said to be an equipment if given any $x\in\mathbb{E}_{n}$ and maps in $\mathbb{E}_{n-1}$ $f^{i}:d_{i}x\rightarrow y^{i}$ such that $d_{i}f^{j}=d_{j-1}f^{i}$ for all $i<j$, then there is an object $y\in\mathbb{E}_{n}$ equipped with a map $f:x\rightarrow y$ satisfying the following: i) $d_{i}y=y^{i}$ and $d_{i}f=f^{i}$ for $i=0,\dots,n$ ii) Given any map $h:x\rightarrow z$ in $\mathbb{E}_{n}$ such that $d_{i}h=g^{i}f$ for some $g^{i}:y^{i}\rightarrow d_{i}z$ in $\mathbb{E}_{n-1}$ then there is a unique $g:y\rightarrow z$ such that $h=gf$ and $d_{i}(g)=g^{i}$
Definition 2. Let $A$ be a Hilbert space, and let $x\in UA$. We say that $x$ is supported on a subspace $A_{0}$ of $A$ if whenever $f,g:A\to B$ are such that $fi_{A_{0},A}=gi_{A_{0},A}$ (where $i_{A_{0},A}$ denotes the inclusion map $A_{0}\to A$), then $f(x)=g(x)$. When $A$ is clear from context, we omit it.
Definition 7. For an infinite-dimensional Hilbert space $A$ and $x\in UA$, we call the minimal subspace of $A$ on which $x$ is supported (given by Lemma 6) the support of $x$ (in $A$). We say that this support is trivial if it is the zero space, nontrivial otherwise.
Definition 2.3. Let $A_{\flat}=\left\{\left[f\right]\in A:f\textrm{ satisfies Condition \ref{con:% Aflat}}\right\}$ Note that $A\mapsto A_{\flat}$ is a functor, whose maps are given by restriction, that is, if $\alpha:A\rightarrow B$, $\alpha_{\flat}:A_{\flat}\rightarrow B_{\flat}$ is simply the restriction of $\alpha$ to $A_{\flat}$.
Definition 4.1 For any bicategory $\mathfrak{C}$, the bicategory of representations of a 2-group $\mathbb{G}$ on $\mathfrak{C}$, denoted $\mathfrak{Rep}_{\mathfrak{C}}(\mathbb{G})$, is the pseudofunctor bicategory $\mathfrak{Rep}_{\mathfrak{C}}(\mathbb{G}):=[\underline{\mathbb{G}},\mathfrak{C}]$ Objects in $\mathfrak{Rep}_{\mathfrak{C}}(\mathbb{G})$ are called representations of $\mathbb{G}$ on $\mathfrak{C}$, while 1- and 2-morphisms are respectively called 1- and 2-intertwiners. A representation $\mathcal{F}:\underline{\mathbb{G}}\rightarrow\mathfrak{C}$ (resp. a 1-intertwiner $\xi:\mathcal{F}\rightarrow\mathcal{F}^{\prime}$) is called strict when the pseudofunctor $\mathcal{F}$ is a 2-functor (resp. when the pseudonatural transformation $\xi$ is a 2-natural transformation).
Definition 6.18 The data $({\bf R},s,{\sf S})$ defining a 1-intertwiner $\xi:(n,\rho,\beta,c)\rightarrow(n^{\prime},\rho^{\prime},\beta^{\prime},c^{% \prime})$ will respectively be called rank matrix, gauge and weakening maps of $\xi$. The 1-intertwiner is called gauge trivial when $s={\bf I}$, the trivial gauge defined in Section 5, and it is called strict when all its weakening maps are trivial (i.e., ${\sf S}_{i^{\prime},i}(g)={\bf I}_{R_{i^{\prime},i}}$ for all $g\in\pi_{0}(\mathbb{G})$ and $(i^{\prime},i)\in{\rm Sup}({\bf R})$; such 1-intertwiners correspond to 2-natural transformations between the involved pseudofunctors as defined in Definition 2.2).
Definition 6.32 A character of a 2-group $\mathbb{G}$ is a 1-dimensional 2-matrix representation of $\mathbb{G}$.
Definition 3.8 Let $\mathbb{F},\widetilde{\mathbb{F}}:\mathbb{G}\rightarrow\mathbb{G}^{\prime}$ be morphisms of 2-groups. A monoidal natural transformation from $\mathbb{F}$ to $\widetilde{\mathbb{F}}$ is a natural transformation $\tau:\mathbb{F}\Rightarrow\widetilde{\mathbb{F}}$ such that the diagrams $\xymatrix{F(A)\otimes^{\prime}F(B)\ar[rr]^{F_{2}(A,B)}\ar[d]_{\tau_{A}\otimes^% {\prime}\tau_{B}}&&F(A\otimes B)\ar[d]^{\tau_{A\otimes B}}\\ \widetilde{F}(A)\otimes^{\prime}\widetilde{F}(B)\ar[rr]_{\widetilde{F}_{2}(A,B% )}&&\widetilde{F}(A\otimes B)}\quad\xymatrix{F(I)\ar[rr]^{\tau_{I}}\ar[rd]_{F_% {0}}&&\widetilde{F}(I)\ar[ld]^{\widetilde{F}_{0}}\\ &I^{\prime}&}$ commute for all objects $A,B$ of $\mathbb{G}$.
Definition 5.4 The 2-category of 2-matrices over $K$, denoted ${\bf 2Mat}_{K}$, is the 2-category defined by the following data: • objects: the natural numbers $n\geq 0$. • 1-morphisms: if $n,m\geq 1$, a 1-morphism $n\rightarrow m$ is a pair $({\bf R},s)$, where (i) ${\bf R}=(R_{ij})$ is an $m\times n$ matrix with entries in $\mathbb{N}$, and (ii) $s$ is a collection of $m$ fields $s_{1},\ldots,s_{m}$ of invertible matrices over $\mathbb{N}^{n}$, with $s_{i}({\bf a})\in{\rm GL}({\bf R}({\bf a})_{i})$ for all ${\bf a}\in\mathbb{N}^{n}$ such that ${\bf R}({\bf a})_{i}\neq 0$ and $s_{i}({\bf a})=1$ otherwise, and satisfying the normalization condition $s_{i}({\bf e}_{j})={\bf I}_{R_{ij}},\quad i=1,\ldots,m,\ j=1,\ldots,n$ whenever ${\bf R}({\bf e}_{j})_{i}\neq 0$ (otherwise, it is equal to 1). In particular, for any $n,m\geq 1$, there is a zero 1-morphism, denoted ${\bf 0}_{n,m}$ and defined by the $m\times n$ zero matrix and the unique possible gauge. R is called the rank matrix and $s$ the gauge of the 1-morphism. When $n=0$ and/or $m=0$, there is only one 1-morphism $n\rightarrow m$, also denoted by ${\bf 0}_{n,m}$. • 2-morphisms: given objects $n,m\geq 1$ and 1-morphisms $({\bf R},s),({\bf R}^{\prime},s^{\prime}):n\rightarrow m$, with ${\bf R}=(R_{ij})$ and ${\bf R}^{\prime}=(R^{\prime}_{ij})$, a 2-morphism $({\bf R},s)\Rightarrow({\bf R}^{\prime},s^{\prime})$ is an $m\times n$ matrix T whose $(i,j)$ entry ${\sf T}_{ij}$ is an $R^{\prime}_{ij}\times R_{ij}$ complex matrix if both $R_{ij},R^{\prime}_{ij}\neq 0$ and empty otherwise. If $n=0$ and/or $m=0$, both 1-morphisms are necessarily equal and there is a unique 2-morphism between them denoted $1_{{\bf 0}_{n,m}}$ (obviously, it is the identity 2-morphism of ${\bf 0}_{n,m}$). • composition of 1-morphisms: if $({\bf R},s):n\rightarrow m$ and $(\widetilde{{\bf R}},\widetilde{s}):m\rightarrow p$, with $n,m,p\geq 1$, their composite $(\widetilde{{\bf R}},\widetilde{s})\circ({\bf R},s):n\rightarrow p$ is the pair $(\widetilde{{\bf R}},\widetilde{s})\circ({\bf R},s)=(\widetilde{{\bf R}}{\bf R% },\widetilde{s}\ast s)$ where $\widetilde{{\bf R}}{\bf R}$ denotes the usual matrix product and $\widetilde{s}\ast s$ is defined by $\displaystyle(\widetilde{s}\ast s)_{k}({\bf a})=\widetilde{s}_{k}({\bf R}({\bf a% }))$ $\displaystyle\left(\bigoplus_{i=1}^{m}{\bf I}_{\widetilde{R}_{ki}}\otimes s_{i% }({\bf a})\right){\bf P}(\widetilde{{\bf R}}_{k},{\bf R},{\bf a})$ $\displaystyle \left(\bigoplus_{j=1}^{n}\ \widetilde{s}_{k}({\bf R}(% {\bf e}_{j}))^{-1}\otimes{\bf I}_{a_{j}}\right)$ for all ${\bf a}\in\mathbb{N}^{n}$ and $k=1,\ldots,p$. Here, ${\bf I}_{0}$ denotes the empty matrix (in particular, any tensor product ${\bf I}_{0}\otimes s_{i}({\bf a})$ is again the empty matrix and it makes no contribution to the previous direct sum) and ${\bf P}(\widetilde{{\bf R}}_{k},{\bf R},{\bf a})$ a suitable permutation matrix of order $\sum_{j=1}^{n}\sum_{i=1}^{m}\widetilde{R}_{ki}R_{ij}a_{j}$. In case one of the numbers $n,m,p$ is zero, the composite is the corresponding zero map. • vertical composition of 2-morphisms: given 2-morphisms ${\sf T}:({\bf R},s)\Rightarrow({\bf R}^{\prime},s^{\prime})$ and ${\sf T}^{\prime}:({\bf R}^{\prime},s^{\prime})\Rightarrow({\bf R}^{\prime% \prime},s^{\prime\prime})$, with $({\bf R},s),({\bf R}^{\prime},s^{\prime}),({\bf R}^{\prime\prime},s^{\prime% \prime}):n\rightarrow m$ and $n,m\geq 1$, the vertical composite ${\sf T}^{\prime}\cdot{\sf T}$ is the matrix obtained by multiplying componentwise both matrices T and ${\sf T}^{\prime}$, i.e. $({\sf T}^{\prime}\cdot{\sf T})_{ij}={\sf T}^{\prime}_{ij}{\sf T}_{ij},\quad i=% 1,\ldots,m,\ j=1,\ldots,n$ where we agree that the product of a matrix by the empty matrix is the empty matrix or the appropriate zero matrix when convenient (for example, it can be $R^{\prime}_{ij}=0$, so that ${\sf T}_{ij}={\sf T}^{\prime}_{ij}=\emptyset$, but $R_{ij},R^{\prime\prime}_{ij}\neq 0$; the matrix $({\sf T}^{\prime}\cdot{\sf T})_{ij}$ is then the $R^{\prime\prime}_{ij}\times R_{ij}$ zero matrix rather than the empty one). • horizontal composition of 2-morphisms: given 2-morphisms ${\sf T}:({\bf R},s)\Rightarrow({\bf R}^{\prime},s^{\prime}):n\rightarrow m$ and $\widetilde{{\sf T}}:(\widetilde{{\bf R}},\widetilde{s})\Rightarrow(\widetilde{% {\bf R}}^{\prime},\widetilde{s}^{\prime}):m\rightarrow p$, with $n,m,p\geq 1$, the horizontal composite $\widetilde{{\sf T}}\circ{\sf T}$ is the $p\times n$ matrix with entries defined by $(\widetilde{{\sf T}}\circ{\sf T})_{kj}=\widetilde{s}^{\prime}_{k}({\bf R}^{% \prime}({\bf e}_{j}))\left(\bigoplus_{i=1}^{m}\ \widetilde{{\sf T}}_{ki}% \otimes{\sf T}_{ij}\right)\widetilde{s}_{k}({\bf R}({\bf e}_{j}))^{-1}$ for all $j=1,\ldots,n$ and $k=1,\ldots,p$, where we agree again that the tensor product of any matrix by the empty matrix is the empty matrix. • identity 1-morphisms: for $n\geq 1$, ${\rm{id}}_{n}$ is the pair $({\bf I}_{n},{\bf I})$, where I denotes the trivial gauge, namely, the gauge $s$ such that, for any ${\bf a}\in\mathbb{N}^{n}$ and $i=1,\ldots,n$, $s_{i}({\bf a})\in{\rm GL}(a_{i})$ is the identity matrix if $a_{i}\neq 0$ and equal to 1 otherwise. • identity 2-morphisms: for any 1-morphism $({\bf R},s):n\rightarrow m$, ${\bf 1}_{({\bf R},s)}$ is the $m\times n$ matrix given by $({\bf 1}_{({\bf R},s)})_{ij}={\bf I}_{R_{ij}}$ if $R_{ij}\neq 0$ and empty otherwise.
Definition 2.2 Let $\mathfrak{C},\mathfrak{D}$ be bicategories and $\mathcal{F},\mathcal{F}^{\prime}:\mathfrak{D}\rightarrow\mathfrak{C}$ pseudofunctors. A pseudonatural transformation $\xi:\mathcal{F}\rightarrow\mathcal{F}^{\prime}$ consists of the following set of data: (D1) For every object $X$ of $\mathfrak{D}$, a 1-morphism $\xi_{X}:\mathcal{F}(X)\rightarrow\mathcal{F}^{\prime}(X)$ in $\mathfrak{C}$. (D2) For every ordered pair $(X,Y)$ of objects in $\mathfrak{D}$, a natural isomorphism $\xi_{2}^{X,Y}:c^{\mathfrak{C}}_{\mathcal{F}(X),\mathcal{F}^{\prime}(X),% \mathcal{F}^{\prime}(Y)}(\xi_{X},-)\circ\mathcal{F}^{\prime}_{X,Y}\Rightarrow c% ^{\mathfrak{C}}_{\mathcal{F}(X),\mathcal{F}(Y),\mathcal{F}^{\prime}(Y)}(-,\xi_% {Y})\circ\mathcal{F}_{X,Y}$ whose $f$-component ($f:X\rightarrow Y$) is denoted by $\xi_{2}(f):\mathcal{F}^{\prime}(f)\circ\xi_{X}\Rightarrow\xi_{Y}\circ\mathcal{% F}(f)$. Moreover, these data must satisfy the following axioms: (A1) For every path $X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f}}{{\rightarrow}}Y\stackrel{{\scriptstyle g}}{{% \rightarrow}}Z$ in $\mathfrak{D}$, the following diagram commutes: $\xymatrix{\xi_{Z}\circ(\mathcal{F}(g)\circ\mathcal{F}(f))\ar[rrr]^{1_{\xi_{Z}}% \circ\mathcal{F}_{2}(g,f)}&&&\xi_{Z}\circ\mathcal{F}(g\circ f)\\ (\xi_{Z}\circ\mathcal{F}(g))\circ\mathcal{F}(f)\ar[u]^{a_{\xi_{Z},\mathcal{F}(% g),\mathcal{F}(f)}}&&&\mathcal{F}^{\prime}(g\circ f)\circ\xi_{X}\ar[u]_{\xi_{2% }(g\circ f)}\\ (\mathcal{F}^{\prime}(g)\circ\xi_{Y})\circ\mathcal{F}(f)\ar[u]^{\xi_{2}(g)% \circ 1_{\mathcal{F}(f)}}&&&(\mathcal{F}^{\prime}(g)\circ\mathcal{F}^{\prime}(% f))\circ\xi_{X}\ar[u]_{\mathcal{F}^{\prime}_{2}(g,f)\circ 1_{\xi_{X}}}\ \\ \mathcal{F}^{\prime}(g)\circ(\xi_{Y}\circ\mathcal{F}(f))\ar[u]^{a^{-1}_{% \mathcal{F}^{\prime}(g),\xi_{Y},\mathcal{F}(f)}}&&&\mathcal{F}^{\prime}(g)% \circ(\mathcal{F}^{\prime}(f)\circ\xi_{X})\ar[lll]^{1_{\mathcal{F}^{\prime}(g)% }\circ\xi_{2}(f)}\ar[u]_{a^{-1}_{\mathcal{F}^{\prime}(g),\mathcal{F}^{\prime}(% f),\xi_{X}}}}$ (A2) For any object $X$ of $\mathfrak{D}$, the following diagram commutes: $\xymatrix{\xi_{X}\circ{\rm{id}}_{\mathcal{F}(X)}\ar[rr]^{l^{-1}_{\xi_{X}}\circ r% _{\xi_{X}}}&&{\rm{id}}_{\mathcal{F}^{\prime}(X)}\circ\xi_{X}\\ \xi_{X}\circ\mathcal{F}({\rm{id}}_{X})\ar[u]^{1_{\xi_{X}}\circ\mathcal{F}_{0}(% X)}&&\mathcal{F}^{\prime}({\rm{id}}_{X})\circ\xi_{X}\ar[ll]^{\xi_{2}({\rm{id}}% _{X})}\ar[u]_{\mathcal{F}^{\prime}_{0}(X)\circ 1_{\xi_{X}}}}$ When all structural 2-isomorphisms $\xi_{2}(f)$ are identities, $\xi$ is called a 2-natural transformation.
