Definition 2.1 Let $\mathfrak{C},\mathfrak{D}$ be any bicategories. A pseudofunctor $\mathcal{F}:\mathfrak{D}\rightarrow\mathfrak{C}$ consists of the following set of data: (D1) For every object $X$ of $\mathfrak{D}$, an object $\mathcal{F}(X)$ of $\mathfrak{C}$. (D2) For every ordered pair $(X,Y)$ of objects in $\mathfrak{D}$, a functor $\mathcal{F}_{X,Y}:\mathfrak{D}(X,Y)\rightarrow\mathfrak{C}(\mathcal{F}(X),% \mathcal{F}(Y))$ (for short, we shall write $\mathcal{F}(*)$ instead of $\mathcal{F}_{X,Y}(*)$, for $*$ any object or morphism in $\mathfrak{D}(X,Y)$). (D3) For every ordered triple $(X,Y,Z)$ of objects in $\mathfrak{D}$, a natural isomorphism $\mathcal{F}_{2}^{X,Y,Z}:c^{\mathfrak{C}}_{\mathcal{F}(X),\mathcal{F}(Y),% \mathcal{F}(Z)}\circ(\mathcal{F}_{X,Y}\times\mathcal{F}_{Y,Z})\Rightarrow% \mathcal{F}_{X,Z}\circ c^{\mathfrak{D}}_{X,Y,Z}$ (the $c$’s denote composition functors in the corresponding bicategory), whose $(f,g)$-component ($f:X\rightarrow Y$, $g:Y\rightarrow Z$) is denoted by $\mathcal{F}_{2}(g,f):\mathcal{F}(g)\circ\mathcal{F}(f)\Rightarrow\mathcal{F}(g% \circ f)$. (D4) For any object $X$ of $\mathfrak{D}$, a 2-isomomorphism $\mathcal{F}_{0}(X):\mathcal{F}({\rm{id}}_{X})\Rightarrow{\rm{id}}_{\mathcal{F}% (X)}$. Moreover, these data must satisfy the following axioms: (A1) For every path $X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f}}{{\rightarrow}}Y\stackrel{{\scriptstyle g}}{{% \rightarrow}}Z\stackrel{{\scriptstyle h}}{{\rightarrow}}T$ in $\mathfrak{D}$, the following diagram commutes: $\xymatrix{\mathcal{F}(h)\circ(\mathcal{F}(g)\circ\mathcal{F}(f))\ar[rrr]^{1_{% \mathcal{F}(h)}\circ\mathcal{F}_{2}(g,f)}&&&\mathcal{F}(h)\circ\mathcal{F}(g% \circ f)\ar[d]^{\mathcal{F}_{2}(h,g\circ f)}\\ (\mathcal{F}(h)\circ\mathcal{F}(g))\circ\mathcal{F}(f)\ar[u]^{a_{\mathcal{F}(h% ),\mathcal{F}(g),\mathcal{F}(f)}}\ar[d]_{\mathcal{F}_{2}(g,f)\circ 1_{\mathcal% {F}(h)}}&&&\mathcal{F}(h\circ(g\circ f))\\ \mathcal{F}(h\circ g)\circ\mathcal{F}(f)\ar[rrr]_{\mathcal{F}_{2}(h\circ g,f)}% &&&\mathcal{F}((h\circ g)\circ f)\ar[u]_{\mathcal{F}(a_{h,g,f})}}$ (A2) For any 1-morphism $f:X\rightarrow Y$, the following diagrams commute: $\xymatrix{\mathcal{F}(f)\circ\mathcal{F}({\rm{id}}_{X})\ar[rr]^{\mathcal{F}_{2% }(f,{\rm{id}}_{X})}\ar[d]_{1_{\mathcal{F}(f)}\circ\mathcal{F}_{0}(X)}&&% \mathcal{F}(f\circ{\rm{id}}_{X})\ar[d]^{\mathcal{F}(r_{f})}\\ \mathcal{F}(f)\circ{\rm{id}}_{\mathcal{F}(X)}\ar[rr]_{r_{\mathcal{F}(f)}}&&% \mathcal{F}(f)}\quad\xymatrix{\mathcal{F}({\rm{id}}_{Y})\circ\mathcal{F}(f)\ar% [rr]^{\mathcal{F}_{2}({\rm{id}}_{Y},f)}\ar[d]_{\mathcal{F}_{0}(Y)\circ 1_{% \mathcal{F}(f)}}&&\mathcal{F}({\rm{id}}_{Y}\circ f)\ar[d]^{\mathcal{F}(l_{f})}% \\ {\rm{id}}_{\mathcal{F}(Y)}\circ\mathcal{F}(f)\ar[rr]_{l_{\mathcal{F}(f)}}&&% \mathcal{F}(f)}$ The pseudofunctor is called a 2-functor when the 2-isomorphisms $\mathcal{F}_{2}(g,f)$ and $\mathcal{F}_{0}(X)$ are all identities.
Definition 6.15 Given triples $(n,\rho,\beta)$ and $(n^{\prime},\rho^{\prime},\beta^{\prime})$ as before, by an $\left(\begin{array}[]{c}n\ \rho\ \beta\\ n^{\prime}\rho^{\prime}\beta^{\prime}\end{array}\right)$-admissible rank matrix we mean a rank matrix ${\bf R}\in{\rm Mat}_{n^{\prime}\times n}(\mathbb{N})$ satisfying conditions (6.24) and (6.25). Moreover, if ${\bf R}\in{\rm Mat}_{n^{\prime}\times n}(\mathbb{N})$ is a $(\rho,\rho^{\prime})$-invariant rank matrix and $g\in\pi_{0}(\mathbb{G})$, a pair $(i^{\prime},i)\in\{1,\ldots,n^{\prime}\}\times\{1,\ldots,n\}$ is called $({\bf R},g)$-admissible if $R_{i^{\prime},\rho(g)(i)}\neq 0$ (equivalently, if $R_{\rho^{\prime}(g)^{-1}(i^{\prime}),i}\neq 0$). The set of such points is denoted by ${\rm Sup}({\bf R},g)$.
Definition 3.17 A 2-group $\mathbb{G}$ is called split if its classifying cohomology class is $[\alpha]=0$.
Definition 3.2 (Bicategory point of view) A 2-group is a bigroupoid with only one object, i.e., a bicategory with only one object and such that all 1-morphisms are equivalences and all 2-morphisms are isomorphisms.
Definition 3.7 Let $\mathbb{G}$, $\mathbb{G}^{\prime}$ be 2-groups (viewed as monoidal categories). A morphism of 2-groups $\mathbb{F}:\mathbb{G}\rightarrow\mathbb{G}^{\prime}$ is a pair $\mathbb{F}=(F,F_{2})$, where $F:\mathbb{G}\rightarrow\mathbb{G}^{\prime}$ is a functor and $F_{2}$ (the monoidal structure of $F$) is a collection of natural isomorphisms $F_{2}(A,B):F(A)\otimes^{\prime}F(B)\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\cong}}{{\rightarrow% }}F(A\otimes B)$, for all objects $A,B$ in $\mathbb{G}$, making commutative the diagrams $\xymatrix{F(A)\otimes^{\prime}(F(B)\otimes^{\prime}F(C))\ar[rrr]^{{\rm{id}}_{F% (A)}\otimes^{\prime}F_{2}(B,C)}&&&F(A)\otimes^{\prime}F(B\otimes C)\ar[d]^{F_{% 2}(A,B\otimes C)}\\ (F(A)\otimes^{\prime}F(B))\otimes^{\prime}F(C)\ar[u]^{a^{\prime}_{F(A),F(B),F(% C)}}\ar[d]_{F_{2}(A,B)\otimes^{\prime}{\rm{id}}_{F(C)}}&&&F(A\otimes(B\otimes C% ))\\ F(A\otimes B)\otimes^{\prime}F(C)\ar[rrr]_{F_{2}(A\otimes B,C)}&&&F((A\otimes B% )\otimes C)\ar[u]_{F(a_{A,B,C})}}$ for all objects $A,B,C$ in $\mathbb{G}$. The morphism $\mathbb{F}$ is called strict when each of the isomorphisms $F_{2}(A,B)$ is an identity and $F(r_{I})=r^{\prime}_{I^{\prime}}$ (equivalently 2Recall that in any monoidal category $(\mathcal{C},\otimes,I,a,l,r)$, the morphisms $r_{I},l_{I}:I\otimes I\rightarrow I$ coincide., $F(l_{I})=l^{\prime}_{I^{\prime}}$).
Definition 5.2 A Kapranov and Voevodsky (finite dimensional) 2-vector space over $K$ is a ${\bf Vect}_{K}$-module category which is ${\bf Vect}_{K}$-module equivalent to ${\bf Vect}_{K}^{n}$ for some $n\geq 0$, called the rank.
Definition 3.3 Let $\mathbb{G}$ be a 2-group. Then: (i) $\mathbb{G}$ is called strict if the underlying monoidal category is strict (i.e., all natural isomorphisms $a,l,r$ are identities) and every object is strictly invertible. (ii) $\mathbb{G}$ is called special if the underlying category is skeletal (i.e., isomorphic objects are equal), the natural isomorphisms $l,r$ are identities and every object is strictly invertible.
Definition 2.4 Given arbitrary bicategories $\mathfrak{C},\mathfrak{D}$, the pseudofunctor bicategory $[\mathfrak{D},\mathfrak{C}]$ is the bicategory whose objects, 1-morphisms and 2-morphisms are respectively the pseudofunctors $\mathcal{F}:\mathfrak{D}\rightarrow\mathfrak{C}$, the pseudonatural transformations and the modifications, and whose composition laws for 1- and 2-morphisms are as defined above.
Definition 3.1 (Category point of view) A 2-group is a monoidal category $(\mathbb{G},\otimes,I,a,l,r)$ which is a groupoid (i.e., all morphisms are isomorphisms) and such that all objects are invertible.
Definition 3.9 The 2-category of 2-groups, denoted ${\sf 2Grp}$, is the 2-category with objects, 1-morphisms and 2-morphisms the 2-groups, the morphisms of 2-groups and the monoidal natural transformations between these, respectively.
Definition 6.4 A 2-matrix representation of $\mathbb{G}$ is called of dimension $n$ ($n\geq 0$) when the objects of $\mathbb{G}$ are represented as autoequivalences of the object $n$ of ${\bf 2Mat}_{\mathbb{C}}$.
2.1 Definition. Let $\hat{S}$ be a superstructure. An $\hat{S}$-small category is a quadruple $\langle M,s,t,c\rangle$ with (i) $M\in\hat{S}\setminus S$, (ii) $s,t:M\rightarrow M$ satisfying (1) $ss=ts=s$, (2) $st=tt=t$, (iii) $c\subseteq M\times M\times M$ satisfying (1) $\forall f,g,h\in M:(\langle f,g,h\rangle\in c)\Rightarrow(sf=tg)\wedge(tf=th)% \wedge(sg=sh)$, (2) $\forall f,g\in M:(sf=tg)\Rightarrow(\exists!h\in M:\langle f,g,h\rangle\in c)$, (iv) $\forall f\in M:\langle f,tf,f\rangle,\langle sf,f,f\rangle\in c$, (v) $\forall f_{1},f_{2},f_{3},f_{12},f_{23},f_{123}\in M:\langle f_{1},f_{2},f_{12% }\rangle,\langle f_{12},f_{3},f_{123}\rangle,\langle f_{2},f_{3},f_{23}\rangle% \in c\Rightarrow\langle f_{1},f_{23},f_{123}\rangle\in c$. If $\mathcal{C}=\langle M,s,t,c\rangle$ is an $\hat{S}$-small category, we call ${\mathrm{Mor}}_{\mathcal{C}}:=M$ the set of morphisms of $\mathcal{C}$.
2.10 Definition. Let $\hat{S}$ be a superstructure. A finite $\hat{S}$-small category is an $\hat{S}$-small category $\mathcal{C}$ whose set morphisms ${\mathrm{Mor}}_{\mathcal{C}}$ is a finite set.
2.4 Definition. Let $\hat{S}$ be a superstructure, and let $\mathcal{C}=\langle M,s,t,c\rangle$ and $\mathcal{D}=\langle M^{\prime},s^{\prime},t^{\prime},c^{\prime}\rangle$ be $\hat{S}$-small categories. A (covariant) functor $F:\mathcal{C}\rightarrow\mathcal{D}$ is a map $F:M\rightarrow M^{\prime}$ satisfying • $Fs=s^{\prime}F$, • $Ft=t^{\prime}F$ and • $\forall f,g,h\in M:\langle f,g,h\rangle\in c\Rightarrow\langle Ff,Fg,Fh\rangle% \in c^{\prime}$.
Definition 2.1. Let $C$ be a stack of pseudo commutative monoids with cancellation (SLCMC). A modular functor on $C$ with labels $\mathcal{M}$ is a (pseudo) morphism $\phi:C\rightarrow C(\mathcal{M})$ of stacks of pseudo commutative monoids with cancellation. A conformal field theory on $C$ with modular functor on labels $\mathcal{M}$ with state space $H$ is a (pseudo) morphism $\Phi:C\rightarrow C(\mathcal{M},H)$ of stacks of pseudo commutative monoids with cancellation.
Definition 3.5. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a 2-category. If $A,B\in Obj\hskip 2.845276pt\mathcal{C}$ and $f,g,h:A\rightarrow B$ are objects of the category $Mor(A,B)$ with 2-cells $\alpha:f\Rightarrow g$ and $\beta:g\Rightarrow h$ then the composition
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be an additive category and let $\mathcal{H}$ be a class of objects in $\mathcal{C}$ containing the zero object and closed under isomorphisms. A cokernel $d:B\to C$ is called an $\mathcal{H}$-semi-stable cokernel if there exists the pullback $(B^{\prime}=B\times_{C}C^{\prime},g,d^{\prime})$ of $d$ along any morphism $h:C^{\prime}\to C$ with $C^{\prime}\in\mathcal{H}$, and $d^{\prime}$ is again a cokernel, i.e. there exists a pullback square $\SelectTips{cm}{}\xymatrix{B^{\prime}\ar[d]_{g}\ar[r]^{d^{\prime}}&C^{\prime}% \ar[d]^{h}\\ B\ar[r]^{d}&C}$ with the morphism $d^{\prime}:B^{\prime}\to C^{\prime}$ a cokernel. The notion of $\mathcal{H}$-semi-stable kernel is defined dually. A short exact sequence, i.e. a kernel-cokernel pair, $A\overset{i}{\to}B\overset{d}{\to}C$ is called $\mathcal{H}$-stable if $i$ is an $\mathcal{H}$-semi-stable kernel and $d$ is an $\mathcal{H}$-semi-stable cokernel. For $\mathcal{H}=\mathcal{C}$ the above concepts particularize to semi-stable kernels, semi-stable kernels and stable short exact sequences.
Definition 4.1. By an exact category we mean an additive category $\mathcal{C}$ endowed with a distinguished class $\mathcal{E}$ of short exact sequences satisfying the axioms $[E0]$, $[E1]$, $[E2]$ and $[E2^{\rm op}]$ below. The short exact sequences in $\mathcal{E}$ are called conflations, whereas the kernels and cokernels appearing in such exact sequences are called inflations and deflations respectively. $[E0]$ The identity morphism $1_{0}:0\to 0$ is a deflation. $[E1]$ The composition of two deflations is again a deflation. $[E2]$ The pullback of a deflation along an arbitrary morphism exists and is again a deflation. $[E2^{\rm op}]$ The pushout of an inflation along an arbitrary morphism exists and is again an inflation.
Definition 6.2 ([16, 7]). The category of labeled higher-dimensional automata is $\text{{{L}}}\text{{{HDA}}}=*\downarrow\text{{{pCub}}}\to\text{{{HDA}}}^{% \mathord{\raisebox{0.86pt}{$\circledcirc$}}}$, with objects $*\to X\to\mathord{!}S$ labeled pointed precubical sets and morphisms commutative diagrams $\xymatrix@C=1.5em@R=1.2em{&{*}\ar[dl]\ar[dr]\\ X\ar[rr]_{f}\ar[d]&&Y\ar[d]\\ {\mathord{!}S}\ar[rr]_{\sigma}&&{\mathord{!}T}}$
Definition 2.1 ([16, 7]). The category of higher-dimensional automata is the comma category $\text{{{HDA}}}=*\downarrow\text{{{pCub}}}$, with objects pointed precubical sets and morphisms commutative diagrams $\xymatrix@C=1.3em@R=1.1em{&{*}\ar[dl]\ar[dr]\\ X\ar[rr]_{f}&&Y\,.}$
Definition 6.9 ([34, Def. 22]). Labeled HDA $*\xrightarrow{i}X\xrightarrow{\lambda}\mathord{!}S$, $*\xrightarrow{j}Y\xrightarrow{\mu}\mathord{!}S$ are history-preserving bisimilar if there exists a relation $R$ between pointed cube paths in $X$ and pointed cube paths in $Y$ for which $((i),(j))\in R$, and such that for all $(\rho,\sigma)\in R$, • $\lambda(\rho)=\mu(\sigma)$, • for all $\rho^{\prime}\sim\rho$, there exists $\sigma^{\prime}\sim\sigma$ with $(\rho^{\prime},\sigma^{\prime})\in R$, • for all $\sigma^{\prime}\sim\sigma$, there exists $\rho^{\prime}\sim\rho$ with $(\rho^{\prime},\sigma^{\prime})\in R$, • for all $\rho^{\prime}\sqsupseteq\rho$, there exists $\sigma^{\prime}\sqsupseteq\sigma$ with $(\rho^{\prime},\sigma^{\prime})\in R$, • for all $\sigma^{\prime}\sqsupseteq\sigma$, there exists $\rho^{\prime}\sqsupseteq\rho$ with $(\rho^{\prime},\sigma^{\prime})\in R$.
Definition 5.1. The category of higher-dimensional automata up to homotopy $\text{{{HDA}}}_{\textup{{h}}}$ has as objects HDA and as morphisms pointed precubical morphisms $f:\tilde{X}\to\tilde{Y}$ of unfoldings.
Definition 6.6. The category of labeled higher-dimensional automata up to homotopy $\text{{{L}}}\text{{{HDA}}}_{\textup{{h}}}$ has as objects labeled HDA $*\to X\to\mathord{!}S$ and as morphisms pairs of precubical morphisms $(f,\sigma):(*\to\tilde{X}\to\mathord{!}\tilde{S})\to(*\to\tilde{Y}\to\mathord{% !}\tilde{T})$ of unfoldings.
Definition 3.1. The category HDP of higher-dimensional paths is the subcategory of HDA which as objects has pointed precubical paths, and whose morphisms are generated by isomorphisms and pointed cube path extensions.
Definition 4.1. The unfolding of a HDA $i:*\to X$ consists of a HDA $\tilde{i}:*\to\tilde{X}$ and a pointed projection morphism $\pi_{X}:\tilde{X}\to X$ which are defined as follows: • $\tilde{X}_{n}=\big{\{}[x_{1},\dots,x_{m}]\mid(x_{1},\dots,x_{m})\text{ pointed% cube path in }X,x_{m}\in X_{n}\big{\}}$; $\tilde{i}=[i]$ • $\tilde{\delta}_{k}^{1}[x_{1},\dots,x_{m}]=[x_{1},\dots,x_{m},\delta_{k}^{1}x_{% m}]$ • $\tilde{\delta}_{k}^{0}[x_{1},\dots,x_{m}]=\big{\{}(y_{1},\dots,y_{p})\mid y_{p% }=\delta_{k}^{0}x_{m},(y_{1},\dots,y_{p},x_{m})\sim(x_{1},\dots,x_{m})\big{\}}$ • $\pi_{X}[x_{1},\dots,x_{m}]=x_{m}$
Definition 6.1. The category of higher-dimensional tori $\text{{{HDA}}}^{\mathord{\raisebox{0.86pt}{$\circledcirc$}}}$ is the full subcategory of pCub generated by the objects $\mathord{!}S$.
